Asked this community a while back if anyone had built e-commerce automation on top of 0nMCP. Got some helpful pointers, so here's the full write-up of what we built.

**The problem:** Our client had Stripe, Shopify, and SendGrid completely disconnected. Orders came in via Shopify, payments processed via Stripe, emails sent manually. Three separate systems with zero automation.

**The architecture using 0nMCP as the MCP integration app:**

```json
{
  "$0n": { "version": "1.0", "type": "workflow" },
  "name": "ecommerce-order-flow",
  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "get_order",
      "service": "shopify",
      "action": "get_order",
      "params": { "order_id": "{{inputs.order_id}}" }
    },
    {
      "id": "create_payment",
      "service": "stripe",
      "action": "create_payment_intent",
      "params": {
        "amount": "{{step.get_order.output.total_price_cents}}",
        "customer_email": "{{step.get_order.output.customer.email}}"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "crm_contact",
      "service": "crm",
      "action": "create_or_update_contact",
      "params": {
        "email": "{{step.get_order.output.customer.email}}",
        "first_name": "{{step.get_order.output.customer.first_name}}"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "confirmation_email",
      "service": "sendgrid",
      "action": "send_email",
      "params": {
        "to": "{{step.get_order.output.customer.email}}",
        "template_id": "d-abc123",
        "dynamic_template_data": {
          "order_id": "{{step.get_order.output.order_number}}"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

The CRM step and email step actually run in Assembly Line mode since they don't depend on each other — that parallel execution saves real time at scale.

**Results after 6 weeks:**
- Zero manual touchpoints for standard orders
- CRM now has complete purchase history for every customer
- Email open rate up 23% (personalization from CRM data)
- Dev time to maintain: basically zero

This is the MCP integration platform pattern for e-commerce. Any questions on the implementation?

We just shipped a new SaaS product and 0nMCP is the entire backend automation layer. I want to document this architecture because it's different from how most people think about an MCP integration app.

**The setup:** Next.js frontend, Supabase for data, Stripe for billing, CRM for customer management. Standard SaaS stack. The non-standard part: 0nMCP runs as an HTTP server (`0nmcp serve --port 3001`) and Next.js API routes call it instead of calling each service directly.

**Why this works better than direct service calls:**

1. Rate limiting is centralized. One token bucket per service, not per-API-route.
2. Credential rotation: update one place (`~/.0n/connections/stripe.0n`), all routes pick it up.
3. Webhook handling: Stripe webhooks hit `POST /webhooks/stripe` on the 0nMCP server directly — HMAC verification built in.
4. AI can use all 558 tools. When we have a support chat feature, Claude has full visibility into what tools are available. It can check a customer's Stripe subscription, look up their CRM record, and respond appropriately — all from one MCP integration platform.

**The pattern for a complex operation (checkout flow):**

```typescript
// Next.js API route
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const { email, plan } = await req.json();

  const result = await fetch('http://localhost:3001/mcp/execute', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify({
      tool: 'stripe_create_checkout_session',
      params: { customer_email: email, price_id: plan }
    })
  });

  return Response.json(await result.json());
}
```

Clean, testable, and the MCP integration app handles auth, retries, and rate limiting.

**The thing I'd do differently:** I'd set up the 0nMCP server as a Docker container from day one rather than running it as a process. We're doing that migration now and it's a bit of work.

Technical implementation of search experience optimization in a Next.js 16 site. This is what we built into 0nmcp.com.

**JSON-LD in Next.js App Router:**

```typescript
// app/forum/[slug]/page.tsx
import { generateForumThreadSchema } from '@/lib/schema';

export default async function ThreadPage({ params }: { params: { slug: string } }) {
  const thread = await getThread(params.slug);
  const schema = generateForumThreadSchema(thread);

  return (
    <>
      <script
        type="application/ld+json"
        dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(schema) }}
      />
      <ThreadContent thread={thread} />
    </>
  );
}
```

**The schema generation function:**

```typescript
export function generateForumThreadSchema(thread: Thread) {
  return {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "DiscussionForumPosting",
    "headline": thread.title,
    "text": thread.body,
    "datePublished": thread.created_at,
    "author": {
      "@type": "Person",
      "name": thread.author_name,
      "url": `https://0nmcp.com/u/${thread.author_id}`
    },
    "url": `https://0nmcp.com/forum/${thread.slug}`
  };
}
```

**AI-powered content for SXO:**
The AI persona system generates forum content seeded with target keywords in natural discussion format. This is different from keyword stuffing — the content is genuinely useful (real technical questions and answers) and happens to include the terms developers search for. That's the search experience optimization principle: satisfy the query with real value.

**Programmatic page generation pattern:**

```typescript
// app/integrations/[slug]/page.tsx
export async function generateStaticParams() {
  return services.map(s => ({ slug: s.slug }));
}

export async function generateMetadata({ params }) {
  const service = getService(params.slug);
  return {
    title: `${service.name} MCP Integration — 0nMCP`,
    description: service.seo_description
  };
}
```

Each of the 26 service pages has unique title, description, and content derived from `services.json`. 26 targeted, server-rendered pages with zero duplication.

This is the SXO implementation stack: server-rendered pages + typed JSON-LD + AI-generated genuine content + programmatic scale.
